07750nam a22009855i 9780774820875DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20112011xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748208757 a10.59962/97807748208752doi  a(DE-B1597)662329  a(OCoLC)1058753226  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHM756bF46 2011eb 7aMED0360002bisacsh04a307.07200aFeminist Community Research :bCase Studies and Methodologies /ced. by Wendy Frisby, Gillian Creese. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2011] 4cÂ©2011  a1 online resource (268 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tUnpacking Relationships in Feminist Community Research -- tCommunity Research from a Post-Colonial Feminist Perspective -- tFeminist Demands, Dilemmas, and Dreams in Introducing Participatory Action Research in a Canada-Vietnam Capacity-Building Project -- tTravels with Feminist Community-Based Research -- tVoices from the Street -- tWorking across Race, Language, and Culture with African and Chinese Immigrant Communities -- tTangled Nets and Gentle Nettles -- tChallenging Policies for Lone Mothers -- tWhite Cowboy, Black Feminism, Indian Stories -- tInside and Outside of the Gates -- tLiving an Ethical Agreement -- tCapacity Building Is a Two-Way Street -- tReflections -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFeminist community research is a collaborative, policy-oriented methodology that holds the promise of empowering the disadvantaged and building a more just society. But in the absence of critical analysis and the responsible use of power, this approach can lead to naive or even harmful practices. Grounded as they are in fieldwork, these interdisciplinary case studies acknowledge the real methodological and ethical issues that researchers can encounter as they negotiate contested research relationships. The authors discuss the strategies -- successful and unsuccessful -- that they have employed to overcome these challenges. The authors' collective experiences working with diverse groups, from immigrant and Aboriginal women in Vancouver to poverty-reduction practitioners in Vietnam, reveal that truly equitable research projects require that we question core concepts and address crucial issues such as the promises and limits of reflexivity; the politics of place, time, and resources; ethical dilemmas and emotional responses; and the way issues of social justice, policy, and social change are embedded in research.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCommunities -- Research. 0aFeminism -- Research. 0aFeminist theory. 7aMEDICAL / Health Policy.2bisacsh1 aAnderson, Joan M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAngeles, Leonora C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBesla, Kashmir, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Helen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuchanan, Marla J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aButterwick, Shauna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCalam, Betty, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChan, Katharine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChettiar, Jill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCreese, Gillian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCreese, Gillian, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFrisby, Wendy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relato